1 ggplot2

1.1 Info

  • R package for making elegant plots quickly
  • Written by Hadley Wickham when he was a graduate student at Iowa State
  • Automatcally deals with spacings, text, titles but also allows you to annotate by adding
  • Superficial similarity to lattice but generally easier/more intuitive
  • Plots are built up in layers Plot the data, overlay a summary, metadata and annotation
  • Works with a data frame

1.2 Components

  • aestheic mappings: how data are mapped to color, size
  • facets: for conditional plots
  • geoms: geometric objects like points, lines, shapes
  • stats: statitcal transformations
  • scales: what scale an aesthetic map uses (example: male = red, female = blue)
  • coordinate system

The basic structure is as follows

ggplot(dataframe, aes(x = , y = )) +

Aesthetics can include x, y, shape, color, fill, and others.

You then add geoms (geom_point(), geom_smooth(), geom_boxplot(), among others).

library(tidyverse)
## Loading tidyverse: ggplot2
## Loading tidyverse: tibble
## Loading tidyverse: tidyr
## Loading tidyverse: readr
## Loading tidyverse: purrr
## Loading tidyverse: dplyr
## Conflicts with tidy packages ----------------------------------------------
## filter(): dplyr, stats
## lag():    dplyr, stats
ggplot(mtcars, aes(x = cyl, y = mpg)) + 
  geom_point()

ggplot(mtcars, aes(x = as.factor(cyl), y = mpg, fill = as.factor(vs))) + 
  geom_boxplot()

ggplot(mtcars, aes(x = hp, y = mpg, shape = as.factor(vs))) + 
  geom_point() 

ggplot(mtcars, aes(x = as.factor(cyl), y = mpg)) + 
  geom_boxplot() + 
  facet_grid(as.factor(vs) ~ .)

2 Download data from the internet

We can download a file from the internet directly in R.

# Optionally assign the url to an object 
fileUrl <- 'https://dl.dropboxusercontent.com/u/7256527/data.csv'

# Download file 
download.file(fileUrl, destfile = "./data.csv", method = "curl")

3 Data reformatting

3.1 Wide to long

set.seed(1)
wide <- data.frame(
  participant = c("p1", "p2", "p3", "p4", "p5", "p6"), 
  info = c("g1m", "g1m", "g1f", "g2m", "g2m", "g2m"),
  day1score = rnorm(n = 6, mean = 80, sd = 15), 
  day2score = rnorm(n = 6, mean = 88, sd = 8)
)

print(wide)
##   participant info day1score day2score
## 1          p1  g1m  70.60319  91.89943
## 2          p2  g1m  82.75465  93.90660
## 3          p3  g1f  67.46557  92.60625
## 4          p4  g2m 103.92921  85.55689
## 5          p5  g2m  84.94262 100.09425
## 6          p6  g2m  67.69297  91.11875

As you can see, this data set is in wide format. In order to do most analyses, we want tidy data. That is, each column should represent a variable and each row should represent an observation. A simple way to reformat the data is with the gather() function from the tidyr package. The basic format is as follows:

gather(df, key = groupingVar, val = dv)
library(tidyr)

df_long <- gather(data = wide, key = day, val = score, -participant, -info)
print(df_long)
##    participant info       day     score
## 1           p1  g1m day1score  70.60319
## 2           p2  g1m day1score  82.75465
## 3           p3  g1f day1score  67.46557
## 4           p4  g2m day1score 103.92921
## 5           p5  g2m day1score  84.94262
## 6           p6  g2m day1score  67.69297
## 7           p1  g1m day2score  91.89943
## 8           p2  g1m day2score  93.90660
## 9           p3  g1f day2score  92.60625
## 10          p4  g2m day2score  85.55689
## 11          p5  g2m day2score 100.09425
## 12          p6  g2m day2score  91.11875
ggplot(df_long, aes(x = day, y = score)) + 
  geom_boxplot()

3.2 More subsetting with logical statements

  • ==: equal
  • !=: not equal
  • >: greater than
  • <: less than
  • >=: greater than or equal to
  • <=: less than or equal to
  • |: or
  • &: and
# All rows in which `cyl` does not equal 6
mtcars[mtcars$cyl != 6, ]

3.3 Add new variables

We can create new variables in our data frame using logical statements. For example, the following code will create a new variable size. The variable is a factor with two levels: big and small. Any observation in which cyl size is 8 will be assigned big, any cyl size smaller (i.e.not equal to 8) will be assigned small.

mtcars$size <- NA 
mtcars[mtcars$cyl == 8, 'size'] <- 'big'
mtcars[mtcars$cyl != 8, 'size'] <- 'small'
print(mtcars)
